=== Districts Participating in Katsuyama Sagicho === The festival is held in 13 districts of the former {{ill|Katsuyama Town (Fukui)|ja|勝山町|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}: Kamibukuroda, Shimobukuroda, Kamigori, Kamigo, Nakago, Shimogo, Kamilongafuchi, Shimolongafuchi, Tomita, Sawa, Yoshino, Tachikawa, and Motomachi 2-chome. Of these, 12 districts, excluding Tomita, construct 6-meter-tall "yagura" towers for the festival.
=== Festival Highlights === [[File:Katsuyama Sagicho tanzaku.jpg|thumb|250px|Irotanzaku and sacred objects at Katsuyama Sagicho]] [[File:Katsuyama DondoYaki.JPG|thumb|250px|Dondo-Yaki at Katsuyama Sagicho]] ; Sagicho Bayashi Performed using {{ill|Shamisen|ja|三味線|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shinobue|ja|篠笛|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kane|ja|鉦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the "Ohayashi" features distinctive festival songs, including the "Daidzuru" song and "Sagicho Taiko" drumming. The drum is struck in a unique "floating" style. Other songs include "Gotaiken," "Konpira Fune Fune," "Shichome," and "Senyu."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about06.html|title=左義長太鼓・左義長ばやし - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref> ; Eandon These lanterns feature satirical commentary, local concerns, and humorous poems, displayed around yagura towers and intersections. Large eandon include drawings and poems, originating from a tradition allowing commoners to express their sentiments freely.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about07.html|title=赤襦袢・絵行燈 - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref> ; Akajuban Traditionally, wearing a red undergarment signified a young man's coming of age. Today, it remains part of the festival's traditions.<ref name=":0" /> ; Tsukurimono Improvised sculptures crafted from everyday objects, often with humorous or symbolic meanings. Since {{ill|1952|ja|昭和27th year|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a Tsukurimono contest has been held.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about08.html|title=作り物・書き流し - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref> ; Oshie Decorative pressed fabric ornaments, historically part of bridal training for women. ; Irotanzaku Colored strips of paper used as decorations in participating districts. The tradition dates back to the Edo period, evolving into its modern form by {{ill|1982|ja|昭和57th year|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about05.html|title=色短冊 - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref> ; Dondo-Yaki On the second night, sacred decorations are burned at Benten Riverbank in a fire ceremony. This ritual is connected to Shinto purification practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about09.html|title=どんど焼き・後燃やし - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref>
== See Also == * {{ill|Katsuyama Castle Museum|ja|勝山城博物館|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} - Features exhibits on Sagicho, including drumming experiences. * {{ill|Makoto Shiina|ja|椎名誠|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} - Praised the festival in his work, becoming a "Katsuyama Sagicho Ambassador" in {{ill|2010|ja|平成22nd year|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Echitetsu Monogatari|ja|えちてつ物語〜わたし、故郷に帰ってきました。|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} - Features Sagicho drum scenes.
