 women. ; Irotanzaku Colored strips of paper used as decorations in participating districts. The tradition dates back to the Edo period, evolving into its modern form by {{ill|1982|ja|昭和57年|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1982|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about05.html|title=色短冊 - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref> ; Dondo-Yaki On the second night, sacred decorations are burned at Benten Riverbank in a fire ceremony. This ritual is connected to Shinto purification practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.katsuyama.fukui.jp/kankou/sagityo/about/about09.html|title=どんど焼き・後燃やし - 勝山左義長について|accessdate=2020-10-21|publisher=勝山市}}</ref>
== See Also == * {{ill|Katsuyama Castle Museum|ja|勝山城博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katsuyama Castle Museum|qq=}} - Features exhibits on Sagicho, including drumming experiences. * {{ill|Makoto Shiina|ja|椎名誠|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Makoto Shiina|qq=}} - Praised the festival in his work, becoming a "Katsuyama Sagicho Ambassador" in {{ill|2010|ja|平成22nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2010|qq=}}. * {{ill|Echitetsu Monogatari|ja|えちてつ物語〜わたし、故郷に帰ってきました。|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echitetsu Monogatari|qq=}} - Features Sagicho drum scenes.
